<h3>08 Jan 2012</h3>
<!-- : story.html,v 1.4 2013/07/08 00:38:55 johnl Exp $ -->
<p><a name="ms8"><table width="100%"><tr><td alight=left><b><a href="http://www.jl.ly/Internet/ms8.html">Reset, Refresh, Reinfect?</a></b></a></td>
<td align=right><font size=-1>Internet</font></td></tr></table>
<font size="-1">The upcoming Windows 8
<a href="http://www.extremetech.com/computing/112029-windows-8-to-include-built-in-reset-refresh-and-hard-drive-imaging">will</a>
<a href="http://blogs.msdn.com/b/b8/archive/2012/01/04/refresh-and-reset-your-pc.aspx">include</a>
new features to Reset or Refresh your computer.
Reset wipes out your entire disk and restores it to they way it
was when the computer was new, Refresh keeps some files and settings, but
wipes and restores everything else.
Given the propensity of Windows machines to become overrun with malware,
rogue toolbars, cramware, and other unwanted annoyances, a way to get rid
of it all quickly seems like a great idea. But ...
<!--  seemore.showmore.html,v 1.1 2005/10/30 20:41:10 johnl Exp $ -->
<p>
<a href="http://www.jl.ly/Internet/ms8.html?seemore=y" class="seemore">See more ...</a>
</p></font>

